00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:53.970
So what are tiles?

00:00:53.970 --> 00:00:57.050
Well, they're really like, you know, they're

00:00:57.050 --> 00:00:59.360
confusing because they're so simple.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:01.710
It's, you know, what if you could have like

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:05.580
a mini web app as like so many have tried before that

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:09.820
could be embedded in anything safely because it can't touch the

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:10.460
network.

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:12.840
That's essentially the whole story.

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.610
And the idea is that you remove a lot of power because

00:01:15.610 --> 00:01:18.470
you remove network and that's significant for people who do,

00:01:18.470 --> 00:01:20.930
you know, network things.

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:26.610
But this reduction in power makes it possible to use this in

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:31.030
many more contexts that are potentially security or privacy sensitive, such

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:32.230
as social media.

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:36.440
And so that is pretty cool, especially since the web is

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:37.480
pretty powerful.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:40.000
So you can build like all kinds of stuff with these.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:42.770
These are, you know, examples of like widgets of all

00:01:42.770 --> 00:01:44.620
kinds that could easily be tiles.

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:48.100
And the thing is like, what's new about this?

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:51.820
Like many people have tried the web app thing before and well

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:54.940
, we haven't heard back from them in 20 years.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:57.350
Like I remember like, if you're, if you're

00:01:57.350 --> 00:01:58.850
, if you're, if you're, if you're

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:03.130
really old like me, you'll remember the XML packaging initiative

00:02:03.130 --> 00:02:05.390
that was trying to put like XHTML and SV

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:07.910
G inside some kind of thing that you could run as an

00:02:07.910 --> 00:02:10.340
app and that, you know, all that.

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:13.480
There have been every two to three years, the W3

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:16.290
C has some kind of workshop about web apps and like,

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:18.720
really, maybe guys, we could be solving this at some

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:19.780
point, perhaps.

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:23.420
And there's progress every time, but it's pretty slow

00:02:23.420 --> 00:02:23.680
.

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:26.500
And of course, like, you know, you can always

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:28.620
use iframes if you don't mind like exf

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:30.790
iltrating a ton of information.

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:33.280
So, you know, this is something that, that,

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:34.910
that's been tried many times.

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:37.950
The things that, the thing that hasn't been properly tried

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:41.000
is just like cutting off the network.

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:43.280
And that's where things can, can, I think,

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:44.590
get quite interesting.

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:47.420
And so the anatomy of a tile is basically, it's

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:49.440
a small secluded web runtime.

00:02:49.450 --> 00:02:54.580
It can load things that are listed in its manifest.

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:57.570
One of the values of tiles is that they don't have

00:02:57.650 --> 00:02:58.950
to be in a zip file.

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:01.350
Like a lot of the time, like a lot of these

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:03.820
things like widgets, I worked on W3C widgets and

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:06.020
all that, they had to be in a zip, which

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:09.430
means that you can only start showing something after you've loaded

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:12.080
the whole zip, because you don't know where the index

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:14.210
is, you don't know if you have all the resources

00:03:14.210 --> 00:03:15.290
you need, yada, yada.

00:03:15.310 --> 00:03:18.070
If you have a video, your zip might be gigabytes big

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:19.870
, it's all, it's all problematic.

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:22.300
So that some people have tried to do stuff around that,

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:24.040
but it's usually not great.

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:27.370
In this case, you know, you load the manifest over

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:29.690
80, if they are stored on 80, or you could

00:03:29.980 --> 00:03:32.560
load it over HTTP, it's going to be pretty small

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:32.820
.

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:37.200
And then dynamically setting up a service worker or something like that

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:38.760
, you see what you need to load.

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:40.940
And if you don't need to load everything, maybe you

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.030
're not watching the video that's included in that thing,

00:03:43.030 --> 00:03:44.060
that's perfectly fine.

00:03:44.170 --> 00:03:47.280
You could have like an entire archive of many things in a

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:50.380
tile without ever having to worry about it.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:53.500
If we look at like basically, you know, this is

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.200
a pdsls of a tile that was published on

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.040
80 proto, most of the fields are pretty straightforward.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.000
If you look, if you've seen web app manifest,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.730
straight out of web app manifest, there's like an icon

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:05.310
, there's a name, there's a description.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:11.190
And one thing that's specific to tiles, and that really

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:14.250
helps solve this idea of like content addressable apps that you

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:17.730
can just like move around and publish in different contexts in a

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:21.080
way that's completely reusable, is that it has this resources

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.400
thing that maps proper web paths.

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:26.580
So like slash is mapped to this like blob of HTML,

00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:30.970
and like slash image dot whatever is mapped to like a C

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:32.030
ID of this.

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:37.130
And these things get to have proper HTTP headers.

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:41.510
In a lot of previous iterations of content addressed web things,

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:43.360
the headers were not included.

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:46.080
So you're getting the content, but without the HTTP headers

00:04:46.250 --> 00:04:48.650
, you don't have the proper context, they might interpret

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:51.500
differently in different in different contexts.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.340
And then you're like in a crazy world.

00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:55.430
And so like, really, that's that's about it

00:04:55.430 --> 00:04:55.630
.

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.460
One of the things that's great is that this example shows

00:04:58.460 --> 00:04:59.540
them stored on 80.

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:02.170
But you could store this anywhere, it really doesn't matter

00:05:02.170 --> 00:05:05.430
, because everything's content addressed throughout the stack.

00:05:05.430 --> 00:05:07.260
So you can put them in the car file, you can

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:09.400
put them over HTTP, you can load them with razz

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:11.020
le, so you can razzle dazzle, all

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:12.300
of that's pretty cool.

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:16.540
And so essentially, you know, that's, that's

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:19.020
it, you know, it's just like, it's

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:21.850
this basically this small contained thing.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:26.510
And what makes it interesting is when you start integrating it in

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:28.840
context and giving it extra power.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.580
So the idea is that the embedding context can say like

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:34.280
, oh, hey, this tile actually, I know what

00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:36.740
's safe for it, I can give it access to this

00:05:36.740 --> 00:05:39.100
specific thing that I've controlled, and you're going to

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.940
see a number of demos of precisely that pattern in action.

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.040
But that's it, like, because you've removed the

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:47.260
power, then you can decide what you give to it.

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:49.380
And so I'm just going to go through a list of

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:51.660
like, and these are most of these are fakes,

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:55.440
except for a couple ones, of like, how to put

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:58.770
them in different contexts, like very simply, you could have

00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:01.650
a game in your social media stream, just like in your

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.440
feed, you're scrolling by, and they're like,

