00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:24.330
And of course, because it's loading off a PDS

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:25.420
, you can paywall it.

00:06:25.460 --> 00:06:28.560
So like, there's a business model even potentially behind that

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:28.740
.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:32.100
You can also do long form, I can give you the

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.300
slides afterwards, don't have to take pictures.

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:36.140
You can do long form.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:39.330
So this is one of, this is a blog post I

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:40.380
wrote a while ago.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:42.670
And so you could imagine that in a in the leaflet

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:46.380
kind of interface, instead of like, you know, create

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.080
using the leaflet editor, you could embed your own long

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.850
form source that has your own style and your own, you

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:55.430
know, pictures, fonts, etc, just like as part

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:59.800
of the normal of the normal leaflet publication format.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:02.250
And you click that and it opens and and you just get

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:03.170
the blog posts.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:09.360
Another thing that's interesting is you can have something called wishes

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:09.660
.

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:12.160
So if any, if any of you are familiar with like

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.900
Android intents, or web intents, or stuff like

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:17.280
that, it's sort of a declarative way of saying

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:19.640
like, hey, I'm a piece of functionality, I

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:23.060
'm a tile, and I need someone to edit an image

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:23.800
for me.

00:07:23.810 --> 00:07:25.360
But I don't, I don't want to call a

00:07:25.430 --> 00:07:26.530
specific program.

00:07:26.540 --> 00:07:28.790
And I definitely don't want to do the thing where you

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:30.700
have to save the file to a file system.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:32.830
And then the user has to like figure out what app they

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:34.550
want to use, and then give it back to me.

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:37.260
And I know that dance that's like fucking insane.

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.450
And so what you say is that is, is you say

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:41.430
, hey, I wish to edit.

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.610
So there's always a verb, this type of data,

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:46.240
and here's the data.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:49.550
And it will find for you a tile that knows how to

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:51.220
carry out that wish.

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:53.440
And of course, maybe you have it installed, as we

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:55.810
said earlier, like bookmarking is installing, so that

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:56.760
that's sufficient.

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:59.430
But maybe it's on the network, if it was published

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:01.740
to AT, you can know that it's able to,

00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:04.890
you can find things that are able to handle specific requests.

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:06.830
So you can use the AT data itself.

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:10.220
And this is just an example of like, you clicked edit

00:08:10.290 --> 00:08:14.840
here, and it loaded the image inside a filter editor,

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:15.650
you know, why not?

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:17.570
And then when you hit save, it sends it back.

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.980
And that's that is really simple, but you can integrate

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:22.800
a lot of things in this way with loose coupling.

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:26.300
This is an example of a tile in Rumi.

00:08:27.030 --> 00:08:32.590
The idea, and I really love this pattern, I would

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:35.460
love to like, when you get to that part of like

00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:37.440
building stuff, I would love to work on that.

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:40.570
The idea here is that you can give tiles, and Delta

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:44.040
Chat does that, you can give them a way to just

00:08:44.040 --> 00:08:46.620
write to a data channel of the channel.

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:49.840
And so it shares data, but only with other people who

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:51.180
are on the channel.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:54.580
So you can install a tile to a chat.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:57.180
And what's cool about that, yeah, I know,

00:08:57.180 --> 00:08:58.300
it kind of breaks the brain.

00:08:58.300 --> 00:09:00.630
But like, if you think, if you think about it

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:03.450
, like, a chat is a pair is a security perimeter

00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:03.960
, right?

00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:06.010
There are people who are inside the chat and can read stuff

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:07.980
, and people who are on the outside who can't.

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:10.900
And there's no reason that a chat would like only send

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:11.770
text messages.

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:14.260
Actually, they don't under the hood, they always send

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:15.820
structured something, right?

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:18.640
And so you send a different structured something that's just data

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.940
that like, and so you, you know, user install

00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:25.760
s a tile to the chat room, every, everyone in

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:27.610
the chat room gets to see that tile.

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:30.480
And then the thing is, those things can post messages that

00:09:30.550 --> 00:09:34.100
are basically CRDT that sync state across every instance of

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:36.610
the tile that people in the room see.

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:39.140
And so you can do something instead of like having all these

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:42.060
fucking doodle things that are always ugly, and like,

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:44.160
you lose the link, and you never know which one,

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.980
you just like in your chat, you just like drop a

00:09:47.020 --> 00:09:50.140
time picker thing where you've like configured some options.

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:52.460
And anyone in the chat can answer, and it syncs

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:53.940
the options for everyone.

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:56.380
And you could do that with a document, you could have

00:09:56.480 --> 00:09:58.890
like a shared markdown editor, like let's edit a

